Font Family of an Element

font-family sets out the element's font.
<style>
h2 {
    font-family: Sans-serif;
}
</style>
In this case h2's font is changed to be Sans-serif. In the excercise inbetween the Style tags it should look like:
<style>
  .red-text {
    color: red;
  }

  p {
    font-size: 16px;
    font-family: Monospace;
  }
</style>


Import Google Font

Inorder to import things from other places you need to call it from somewhere else.
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Lobster" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css">

This case the link calls for a lobster font from the fonts.googleapis.com which is a website containing a wide variety of different fonts.
Once you have chosen a font and link it (in between <head> Header </head> tags) , this is then able to be used across the html document.


Specify How Fonts Should Degrade

There are several default fonts:
1. Monospace
2. Sans
3. Sans-serif
Degrade is needed as a backup incase the first font isn't available for use.
p {
    font-family: Helvetica, Sans-Serif;
}
In this case the paragraph is given the font Helvetica but as a backup there is Sans-serif available.
For the example
h2 {font-family: Lobster, Monospace; }  calls for the Lobster font but also provides Monospace as the backup font.


Add Images to your Website

img element also includes src attribute to point to a specific image url.
<img src="https://www.your-image-source.com/your-image.jpg">

A better way to format the 'img' element is to include alt attribute which is used for screen readers to increase accesiblilty and if the image fails to load, provides a way to informr about what the image should contain.

<img src="https://www.your-image-source.com/your-image.jpg" alt="Author standing on a beach with two thumbs up. ">
The excercise requires you to substitute to insert https://bit.ly/fcc-relaxing-cat


Add Borders Around your Elements

CSS borders have properties like style, color and width.
You can add multiple classes to an element by separating each class attribtue.
<img class="class1 class2"> they a seperated by a space.

In the excercise :
<img class="thick-green-border"> enables the use in the Style tags.
<style>
  .thick-green-border {
    border-color: green;
    border-width: 10px;
    border-style: solid;
  }
</style>
This tells the img to have a green coloured border with a width of 10 pixels and solid lines.


Add Rounded Corners with a Border Radius

CSS property called border-radius can be specified with pixels.
 <img class="smaller-image thick-green-border">
 <style>
    .smaller-image {
        width: 100px;
        border-radius: 10px;
    }
 </style>
The img now has two classes smaller image and thick green border.
Adding smaller image to the style enables a change in width and radius to provide a more rounded photo shot.


Make Circular Images with a Border Radius

You can use percentages to specify border-radius.
The excercise requires you to give the cat photo a border-radius of 50%
<style>
    .smaller-image {
        width: 100px;
        border-radius: 50%;
    }
</style>


Link to External Pages with Anchor Element

a elements are known as anchor elemetns which are used to link external content to the current website. It can be inserted in a paragraph text section.
<p> Here's a <a href="http://freecodecamp.com"> Link to freecodecamp </a> to follow.
The excercise requires anchor for cat pgoto page.
<p> Here's a <a href="http://freecatphotoapp.com"> Cat Photos </a> link. </p>


Nest an Anchor Element

Nesting just means putting one element inside of another element.
By now  Full page should look like:
<head>
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Lobster" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css">
<style>
  .red-text {
    color: red;
  }

  h2 {
    font-family: Lobster, Monospace;
  }

  p {
    font-size: 16px;
    font-family: Monospace;
  }

  .thick-green-border {
    border-color: green;
    border-width: 10px;
    border-style: solid;
    border-radius: 50%;
  }

  .smaller-image {
    width: 100px;
  }
</style>
</head>

<body>
    <h2 class="red-text">CatPhotoApp</h2>

    <p> View more
        <a href="http://www.freecatphotoapp.com">cat photos</a>

    </p>

