Use an ID Attribute to Style an Element

id attributes can be used by css just like classes.
e.g. #cat-photo-form {
    background-color: green;
}


Adjusting the Padding of an Element

Three important elements; padding, margin, border
padding controls space between elements and border.

Change the padding of your green box to match that of your red box.
<style>
  .injected-text {
    margin-bottom: -25px;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .box {
    border-style: solid;
    border-color: black;
    border-width: 5px;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .yellow-box {
    background-color: yellow;
    padding: 10px;
  }

  .red-box {
    background-color: red;
    padding: 20px;
  }

  .green-box {
    background-color: green;
    padding: 20px;
  }
</style>
<h5 class="injected-text">margin</h5>

<div class="box yellow-box">
  <h5 class="box red-box">padding</h5>
  <h5 class="box green-box">padding</h5>
</div>


Adjust the Margin of an Element

margin - controls space between an elements border and surrounding elements.
Change the margin of the green box to match the red box.
<style>
 .red-box {
    background-color: red;
    padding: 20px;
    margin: 20px;
  }

  .green-box {
    background-color: green;
    padding: 20px;
    margin: 20px;
  }
</style>


Add a Negative Margin to an Element

Element's margin to a negative value, the element will grow larger.
Change the margin of the green box to -15px to match red box.
<style>
    .red-box {
    background-color: red;
    padding: 20px;
    margin: -15px;
  }

  .green-box {
    background-color: green;
    padding: 20px;
    margin: -15px;
  }
</style>


Add Different Padding to Each Side of an Element

Can customise an element to change padding on different sides.
CSS allows you to control the padding of an element on all four sides with padding-top, padding-right, padding-bottom, and padding-left properties.

Give the green box a padding of 40px on its top and left side, but only 20px on its bottom and right side.
<style>  .green-box {
    background-color: green;
    padding-top: 40px;
    padding-left: 40px;
    padding-right: 20px;
    padding-bottom: 20px;
  }
</style>


Add Different Margins to Each Side of an Element

Can customise an element to change margin on different sides.
CSS allows you to control the margin of an element on all four sides with margin-top, margin-right, margin-bottom, and margin-left properties.
Give the green box a margin of 40px on its top and left side, but only 20px on its bottom and right side.
<style>  .green-box {
    background-color: green;
    margin-top: 40px;
    margin-left: 40px;
    margin-right: 20px;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
  }
</style>



Use Clockwise Notation to Specify the Padding of an Element

You can specify elements padding all on one line.
<Style>
.green-box {
    background-color: green;
    padding: 40px 20px 20px 40px;
  }
</style>


Use Clockwise Notation to Specify the Margin of an Element

You can specify elements margin all on one line.
<style>
  .green-box {
    background-color: green;
    margin: 40px 20px 20px 40px
  }
</style>


Style the HTML Body Element

CSS inheritance
Every HTML page has a body element.
We can prove that the body element exists here by giving it a background-color of black.
<style>
    body {
        background-color: black;
    }
</style>
The body tags <body> </body> are place after the style and head tags.
They completely encase the rest of the html document.


Inherit Styles from the Body Element

Body element in CSS means all the other elements will inherit body element styles.
First, create a h1 element with the text Hello World
<h1> Hello World <h1>

Then, let's give all elements on your page the color of green by adding color: green; to your body element's style declaration.
<style>
    body{
        color: green;
    }
</style>
Finally, give your body element the font-family of Monospace by adding font-family: Monospace; to your body element's style declaration.
<style>
    body{
        font-family: Monospace;
    }
</style>


Prioritize One Style Over Another

Html elements have multiple styles which can often conflict with eachother.
e.g. h1 can't be both green and pink
The overriding colour will be the one selected on the specific element as opposed to the body.
Create a CSS class called pink-text that gives an element the color pink.
Give your h1 element the class of pink-text.

<style>
    .pink-text {
        color:pink;
    }
</style>
    <h1 class="pink-text"> Hello World! </h1>


Override Styles in Subsequent CSS

pink-text class overrode body element css declaration
Create an additional CSS class called blue-text
Apply the blue-text class to your h1 element in addition to your pink-text class
Applying multiple class attributes to a HTML element was covered earlier
class=" class1 class2"

The order doesn't matter when listing in HTML.
Style order of declarations is important and the second option will always override the first.
<style>
 .pink-text {
    color: pink;
  }
  .blue-text {
    color: blue;
  }
</style>
<h1 class="pink-text blue-text">Hello World!</h1>


Override Class Declarations by Styling ID Attributes

Browsers read CSS from top to bottom so a conflict will result in the browser reading the last css declaration:
Another way to override is using id attributes:
make your h1 element orange:
<h1 id="orange-text">
Leave the blue-text and pink-text classes on your h1 element:
<h1 id="orange-text" class="pink-text blue-text"> </h1>
Create a CSS declaration for your orange-text id:
<style>
    #orange-text {
        color:orange;
}
</style>


Override Class Declarations with Inline Styles

id declarations override class declarations, regardless of placement.
in-line style are another way of overriding CSS.

Use an in-line style to try to make our h1 element white:
<h1 id="orange-text" class="pink-text blue-text"  style="color: white">Hello World!</h1>


Override All Other Styles by using Important

in-line styles will override all the CSS declarations in your style element.
Final method to override CSS is most powerful and to be used when using CSS libraries which may result in overriding your existing CSS.
Need to be absolutely sure that an element has specific CSS, you can use !important

!important to your pink-text element's color declaration to make 100% sure that your h1 element will be pink.
<style>
    .pink-text {
        color: pink!important;
    }
</style>


Use Hex Code for Specific Colors

hexidecimal code / hex code - decimals, or base 10 numbers, which use the symbols 0 to 9 for each digit.
Hexadecimals (or hex) are base 16 numbers.
 symbols 0-9 represents values zero to nine and the letters A,B,C,D,E,F represent values ten to fifteen.
 CSS use 6 hexadecimal digits to represent colors, two each for the red (R), green (G), and blue (B) components. E.g. #000000 is black and the lowest possible value.

Replace the word black in our body element's background-color with its hex code representation, #000000:
<style>
  body {
    background-color: #000000;
  }
</style>



Use Hex Code to Mix Colors


E.g. Orange is combination of red, green and no blue = #FFA500
0 is the lowest number in hex code, and represents a complete absence of color.
F is the highest number in hex code, and represents the maximum possible brightness.
Color           Hex Code
Dodger Blue     #2998E4
Green           #00FF00
Orange          #FFA500
Red             #FF0000


Use Abbreviated Hex Code

Hex codes can be shortened.
red = #FF0000 but can be shortened to #F00 one digit red, one digit gree and one digit blue.
Browsers interpret #FF0000 the same as #F00.
Color       Short Hex Code
Cyan        #0FF
Green       #0F0
Red         #F00
Fuchsia     #F0F

<style>
  .red-text {
    color: #F00;
  }
  .fuchsia-text {
    color: #F0F;
  }
  .cyan-text {
    color: #0FF;
  }
  .green-text {
    color: #0F0;
  }
</style>

<h1 class="red-text">I am red!</h1>
<h1 class="fuchsia-text">I am fuchsia!</h1>
<h1 class="cyan-text">I am cyan!</h1>
<h1 class="green-text">I am green!</h1>


Use RGB values to Color Elements

RGB for black = rgb(0, 0, 0,)
RGB for white = rgb(255, 255, 255)
RGB you specify the brightness of each color with a number between 0 and 255.
Replace the hex code in our body element's background color with the RGB value for black: rgb(0, 0, 0)
<style>
  body {
    background-color: rgb(0,0,0);
  }
</style>


Use RGB to Mix Colors

Color       RGB
Blue        rgb(0, 0, 255)
Red         rgb(255, 0, 0)
Orchid      rgb(218, 112, 214)
Sienna      rgb(160, 82, 45)

Replace the color words in our style element with their correct RGB values.
<style>
  .red-text {
    color: rgb(255, 0, 0);
  }
  .orchid-text {
    color:rgb(218, 112, 214);
  }
  .sienna-text {
    color: rgb(160, 82, 45);
  }
  .blue-text {
    color: rgb(0, 0, 255);
  }
</style>

<h1 class="red-text">I am red!</h1>

<h1 class="orchid-text">I am orchid!</h1>

<h1 class="sienna-text">I am sienna!</h1>

<h1 class="blue-text">I am blue!</h1>


